      },
      "date": "2018-01-20 17:33:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nAlex, can we get this patch landed?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "71ed8b7e558c921086af18c1f4210047e6c3f6c5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2018-01-24 13:30:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n(7 comments)\n\nI understand why we need this kind of overhead for ldiskfs where we have no strong consistency checks, etc. but this isn't the case with ZFS which already pays a lot to maintain consistency. now we add more to get essentially nothing. IMO, all this functionality is needed only to migrate from ldiskfs or pure ZFS, so should be done as a standalone utility with own tests and zero Lustre overhead.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "401cd4b262c6582c7d6f54c87b7b3cee6176ea92",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-01-24 15:07:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(7 comments)\n\n> I understand why we need this kind of overhead for ldiskfs where we have no strong consistency checks, etc. but this isn't the case with ZFS which already pays a lot to maintain consistency. now we add more to get essentially nothing. IMO, all this functionality is needed only to migrate from ldiskfs or pure ZFS, so should be done as a standalone utility with own tests and zero Lustre overhead.\n\nAs the ticket description in LU-7585 said, the ZFS OI scrub is not only for data migration between ZFS and ldiskfs, but also for the potential OI corruption.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
